Note that configuration C34-2 may also be used, then a small tapering 
will allow to obtain also 2" to reach our  sensitivity goal.


FREQUENCY SETUP
We propose to use the two following setups:

(1) -LSB: CO@ 230.538 GHz, SO2 @ 226.300 GHz

-USB: HDO @ 241.561 GHz, SO2 @ 244.254 GHz, ClO @ 241.490 GHz;

(2)   LSB: SO @ 219.949 GHz, 13CO @ 220.399 GHz,  and SO2 @ 221.965  
GHz (230 MHz bandwidth) + OCS @ 218.903 GHz and C18O @ 219.560 GHz  
(115 MHz bandwidth). The typical linewidth of weak lines is 2 MHz.



This combination allows to observe, apart from CO and its isotopes, a  
strong line of HDO, a strong line of SO, and 2 strong lines of SO2. It  
favors the observation of SO2 which is more difficult to detect than  
SO, as shown in Fig. 2 The detections of ClO (recently detected at  
JCMT at 352.88 GHz, Sandor &amp; Clancy 2013) and OCS (observed in the  
troposphere only) are unlikely, but the lines are searched for, in  
case of unexpected abundances or strong local variability.



Using the two setups described above, we have estimated the required  
integration times with the ALMA calculator, assuming for minor species  
a spectral resolution of 0.3 MHz (optimal choice adapted for our  
linewidth), and a field of view of 2 arcsec (in agreement with the  
synthetized beam shown in Figure 3). The expected line depths of the  
CO, 13CO, C18O, SO, SO2 and HDO lines in the two setups are shown in  
Figure 4.




SENSITIVITY 
Setup 1 (SO2 and HDO): The SO2 transition at 244.254 GHz is the strongest 
one in band 6 (see Figure 4). The continuum of Venus is 42 Jy. 
The expected depth (for SO2 = 6 ppb) is 0.07%, i.e. 29 mJy/beam. 
In order to achieve  a S/N of 10 with a resolution of 0.3 MHz, 
a sensitivity of 2.9 mJy is required. This implies an observing time of 1 hour on the  
source, i.e. 2.1 hours total time. This will ensure a S/N of about 65  
on the HDO line at 241.561. GHz.

Setup 2 (SO): SO (219.949 GHz). The continuum of Venus is 32 Jy. The  
expected depth (for SO = 4 ppb) is 0.27%, i.e. 88 mJy/beam.  We  
require the same sensitivity of 2.9 mJy as for setup 1. This implies  
an observing time of 0.8 hour on the source, i.e. 1.6 hours total  
time. This will ensure a S/N of about 30 on the SO line at 219.949  
GHz , and about 6 on the SO2  line at 221.965 GHz.

We thus require 2.1 + 1.6 = 3.7 hours of total time. We note that the  
S/N are estimated for mixing ratios of 4 ppb (SO), 6 ppb (SO2) and 1.5  
ppm (H2O) as inferred from our Cycle 0 data. The required observing  
time should allow robust mapping of these species. We know, however,  
that for SO and SO2, variations by factors up to 5 have been observed  
in the past relative to these values (Sandor et al. 2012).


CALIBRATION
Based on our experience on cycle 0 observations, 
a standard RF bandpass measurement of 10 minutes 
on a strong quasar will be enough to measure accurately the 
weak line/continuum ratio on SO,SO2. 
